{{short description|Assasin of George I of Greece}}
[[Image:Aleksandar Schinas.jpg|thumb|Alexandros Schinas]]
[[File:Assassination of George I of Greece, 1913.png|thumb|right|Assassination of [[George I of Greece]] by Alexandros Schinas in 1913 as depicted in a contemporary [[lithograph]]]]

'''Alexandros Schinas''' ({{lang-el|Αλέξανδρος Σχινάς}}) (c.1870 &ndash; May 6, 1913), also known as '''Aleko Schinas''', (in the 1870's, most probably in [[Volos]] where he was the founder of an anarchist school &ndash; May 6, 1913 in [[Thessaloniki]]),  was a [[Greece|Greek]] [[anarchism|anarchist]]{{r|anarchist}} notable for assassinating [[List of Kings of Greece|King]] [[George I of Greece]] in [[Thessaloniki]] in 1913 as an example of propaganda of the deed.{{sfn|Kemp|2018}}{{sfn|Bernhard Blumenau|2013|p=30}}

== Early life ==
Schinas was most probably born in Volos in the 1870's. Schinas studied medicine in univercity of Athens and during that time developed interest on anarchism. There he opened a famous anarchist school in Volos but was shut down by the government.{{sfn|Kemp|2018}}. After spending some time and working in [[New York City]] he returned to Greece in February 1913.{{sfn|Kemp|2018}}{{sfn|Henry E. Mattox|2015|p=22}}. By that time, he was alcoholic and leaning towards anarchism.{{sfn|Kemp|2018}}{{sfn|Tomai|2012|ps=: Tomai presents some primary sources describing Schinas as a weird person with socialist ideas ie that there would not be any more poor or rich people and no one would have to work more than 2 hours per day}}

== Assassination of King George I ==
On March 18, 1913, at around 5:15 PM,Schinas (who was around 40 at the time) shot King George I in the back from a distance of two paces while the king was walking in [[Thessaloniki]], near White Tower.{{sfn|Henry E. Mattox|2015|p=22}} Entering below the king's shoulder blade, the bullet pierced his heart. By the time the king arrived at the hospital, he was already dead.<ref>{{harvnb|Tomai|2012}}</ref>

Schinas was taken into custody immediately, initially refusing to explain the reason for the crime. Later, Schinas declared that he killed the king because the latter refused to give him the money he asked for.<ref name="sorrow">''Sorrow Throughout Greece'', by Marconi Transatlantic Wireless Telegraph; ''The New York Times''; March 19, 1913; pg. 2</ref> The Greek government released statements claiming that Schinas was an alcoholic vagrant.<ref>''The Times (London)''; 20 March 1913; pg. 6</ref>Schinas was tortured throughout the following night, being "forced to undergo examinations", but he refused to give the names of any accomplices.<ref name="NYT320">''The New York Times''; March 20, 1913; pg. 3</ref> On May 6, he died by allegedly jumping out of the window of the gendarmerie in Thessaloniki, but is unclear whether it was a suicide.{{sfn|Kemp|2018}} 

All istorians cites Schinas as educated anarchist.{{sfn|Bernhard Blumenau|2013|p=30}}

