{{notability|Biographies|date=March 2011}} '''Kaushalya Bannerji''' (born [[Calcutta]]<ref>[http://errol.oclc.org/laf/n94-47640.html Library of Congress Name Authority File]</ref>) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] poet.
A resident of [[Toronto]] since 1993, Kaushalya Bannerji is the daughter of the respected activist and intellectual [[Himani Bannerji]].{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} In her [[Article (publishing)|article]]: A Lotus of Another Color, she delved with the [[cultural]] complexities sexuality adds to one's sense of self, and identity especially coming from a [[social conservative]] society. The dilemma is enhanced by the willingness of many lesbians to keep their cultural identity and roots, while confronting the jaundiced opinions of sexuality from the individual's societies.<ref>Karla Jay; Dyke Life: From Growing Up to Growing Old A Celebration of the Lesbian Experience. Basic Books, 1996, pp 40.</ref>
==Selected bibliography== *1993: "No Apologies" in ''A Lotus of Another Color: An Unfolding of the South Asian Gay and Lesbian Experience'', ed. Rakesh Ratti (Boston: Alyson Publications, Inc., ) 59-64. *1995: ''A New Remembrance: Poems'', (Toronto: TSAR, ). *1996: Pearls of Passion: A Treasury of Lesbian Erotica (Ed. Makeda Silvera et al.) (Toronto: Sistervision Press, ) *1998: {{cite book| author = Kaushalya Bannerji| title = The faces of five o'clock| date = 1998-11-11| publisher = Sister Vision Press| isbn = 978-1-896705-10-1 }} *2007: ''Let the Guitar Raise Her Hand, Selected Lyrics of Silvio Rodriguez'' (Translation from Spanish) (Kolkata: Tarjama Press, ) *2012: ''Grandfather's Kingdom, the Prose Poems of Josefina de Diego'' (Translation from Spanish) (Kolkata:Tarjama Press, )
