{{Infobox Muslim scholar |honorific_prefix = [[Grand Ayatollah]] |name = Mohammad Kazem Tabatabei Yazdi |image = Mohammad Kazem Tabataba'i Yazdi.jpg |caption = Grand Ayatollah Muhammad Kazem Yazdi |title = |birth_name = |birth_date = 1831 |birth_place = [[Yazd]], [[Iran]] |death_date = 1919 |death_place = [[Najaf]], [[Iraq]] |death_cause = |resting_place = Najaf, [[Imam Ali Mosque]] |other_names = Sayyid Mohammad Kazem Tabatabei Yazdi |nationality = Iranian |ethnicity = |era = |region = [[Twelver]] [[Shia]] |occupation = |denomination = |jurisprudence = |creed = |movement = |main_interests = [[Islamic philosophy]], [[Usul al-fiqh]] |notable_ideas = |notable_works = [[Urwa al-Wuthqa]] |alma_mater = |Sufi_order = |disciple_of = |influenced = [[Mahdi Hussaini Shirazi]], [[Aqa Bozorg Tehrani]] |module = |website = |signature = }}
'''Mohammed Kazem Yazdi''' ([[Persian language|Persian]]: محمد کاظم یزدی) (born 1831)<ref name="google2">{{cite book|title=The Iranian Constitutional Revolution and the Clerical Leadership of Khurasani|author=Farzaneh, M.M.|date=2015|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=9780815653110|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IIP3CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA214|page=214|accessdate=2017-02-03}}</ref> was a prominent [[Twelver]] [[Shia]] [[Marja']] centered in [[Najaf]], most famous for his anti-constitutionalist stand during the [[Iranian Constitutional Revolution]] of 1905–1911. He is said to have at first reflected the attitude of the "piously apolitical [[ulama]]" and refused to take a stand in favor of the Constitution despite insistent pressure by pro-Constitution talebs, but then opposed the Constitution siding with [[Sheikh Fazlollah Noori]] when Noori's son came to Najaf to enlist clerical support.
In the ensuing reaction against the politicized students in Najaf and the execution of Noori, Yazdi was supported by his Arab followers, the Ottoman governor, and the group known as the "Army of God" (''jond Allah''). His victory over the Constitutionalists and their clerical leader [[Mohammad-Kazem Khorasani]] was "complete," with Yazdi emerging as "the undisputed master of the Holy Cities." According to secular historian [[Ahmad Kasravi]], several thousand would pray behind Yazdi at [[salat]] but only 30 or so prayed behind his rival Khorasani.<ref>*[https://books.google.com/books?id=IQci1YIffjYC&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52 The Turban for the Crown: The Islamic Revolution in Iran By Said Amir Arjomand]</ref>
==Political activity== He disagreed with [[Akhund Khorasani]] in terms of constitutionalism. He thought, in contrary to Akhund Khorasani who allowed a pragmatic approach to constitutionalism, that [[Usuli|Usulism]] does not allow to act freely in supporting constitutionalism. He thought that politics is beyond his expertise and therefore did not take part in politics.<ref name="google2"/> while Akhund Khorasani was an eminent [[Marja']] in [[Najaf]], many imitators prayed behind the kazem Tabataei and it shows that he was an eminent figure along with Akhund Khorasani in religious authority.<ref name="google3">{{cite book|title=The Mantle of the Prophet|author=Mottahedeh, R.|date=2014|publisher=Oneworld Publications|isbn=9781780747385|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=YlsQBwAAQBAJ&pg=PT118|accessdate=2017-02-03}}</ref> In other words both Mohammad Kazem and Khorasani had constituted a great Shia school in Najaf although they had different views in politics at the same time.<ref name="google4">{{cite book|title=Iraq: The ancient sites and Iraqi Kurdistan|author1=Hann, G.|author2=Dabrowska, K.|author3=Greaves, T.T.|date=2015|publisher=Bradt Travel Guides|isbn=9781841624884|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-9RNCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA292|page=292|accessdate=2017-02-03}}</ref> when khorosani died Yazdi elected as supreme Marja. Yazdi supported Fazlull Allah Nuri in terms of opposition to constitution in Iran.<ref name="google5">{{cite book|title=Religion and Politics in Iraq: Muslim Shia Clerics Between Quietism and Resistance|author=Marcinkowski, M.I.|date=2004|publisher=Ibex Pub|isbn=9789971775131|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xJ6GT5YIsygC&pg=PA20|page=20|accessdate=2017-02-03}}</ref>
==Works== One of his important books is ''[[Urwa al-Wuthqa]] (Orwatul Wosgha)''.<ref>[https://hawzah.net/fa/Book/View/45279/26362/1-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%88%D8%AB%D9%82%DB%8C Urwa al-Wuthqa] hawzah.net Retrieved 27 Oct 2018</ref> This book which is in [[Arabic]] is to a collection of legal ruling issued in 1919.<ref name="google6">{{cite book|title=Days of God: The Revolution in Iran and Its Consequences|author=Buchan, J.|date=2013|publisher=Simon & Schuster|isbn=9781416597773|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XY9FAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA377|page=377|accessdate=2017-02-03}}</ref>
